{"/service/ndnp/mdu/batch_mdu_easton_ver02/data/sn89060127/00279521948/1921031901/0097.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE FOUR\nWORCESTER DEMOCRAT\nAND\nTHE LEDGER-ENTERPRISE\nPublished Every Saturday at Pocomoke City, Maryland.\nSAM\u2019L M. CROCKETT, Editor and Proprietor.\nEntered at the Postoffice at Pocomoke City, Maryland as Second Class Matter.\n$1.50 A Year In Advance.\nForeign Advertising Representative\nTHE AMERICAN PRESS ASSOCIATION\nSATURDAY, MARCH 19, 1921.\nWHAT WOULD YOU DO WITH $10.00?\nIn a certain school the question was put to the young people,\n.\"What would you do with $10.00?\u201d Two-thirds of the boys said\nthey would put it into sports, and two-thirds of the girls would\nspend it for clothes.\nParents and teachers should show the young' people of Pocc\nmoke City that money can be used in one of two ways. Tt can be\nemployed for some slight present satisfaction. Or it can be used\nas the foundation on which can be built some great benefit\nlater on.\nIf a boy blew out nis money on a trip to some city and spent\nit on shows an<j( feeds, all benefits therefrom would have disap\npeared the next day. But if he would put in his money to help\nbuy a musical instrument and would go to work taking lessons on\nthe same, he would eventually acquire a resource that would give\nhim pleasure and satisfaction all his life.\nA boy who has been taught to look to future results, will of\nten buy a few chickens, and soon have a little pen filled with valu\nable poultry. This will enable him to staid a bank account, that\neventually will be the foundation of the successful business.\nSome day the boy who put his money into little enterprises of\nhis own, will be a leading business man in Pocomoke City, with a\nfine house and an important position in the life of the city. The\nfellow who blew in the ten spot on a pleasure trip, will be working\nfor meager day wages. The girl who spent all her money on\nclothes will probably be living in a disorderly tenement. The one\nwho put her gift in some useful course of study, will attract the\nof some capable fellow, and in her attractive home will be\nApf the social leaders of the community.\nf 9 \u201cPSYCHOLOGICAL\u201d DEPRESSIONS.\nW President Wilson made a famous remark, when he observed\npthat the business depression of 1914 was merely \u201cpsychological\u201d.\nSo to-day the business depression is mostly psychological, and it\nbecomes a question how our psychology can be modified.\nThe human mind acts by fits and \u201carts. A lot of people pro\nceed to buy all skinds of products very extravagantly, and the cost\nof everything rises beyond all reason. Then people have a fit of\neconomy, and cut their purchases down to the limit. If they had\nbought a good deal less in 1919 they could have bought more\nin 1921.\nWhen people handle their money matters by reason instead of\nby those illogical intuitions called \u201cpsychology,\u201d the business ma\nchine will run better. Reason says that in a period of flush times,\nprices are high, so that it is a good time for economy. In quiet\ntimes like the present, reason says prices are low. So now is a fine\ntime to buy. The stores of Pocomoke City are offering'abundant\nopportunity to stock up against possible higher prices.\nTIME FOR PUBLIC WORK.\none out of ten of the leading business men in any commu\njy, All accept a public office that will take much of his time, or\nA manage the affairs of improvement and welfare orgam-\nHHhH\u00a3 E. Pomeroy, president of the Ohio hoard of commerce.\nS^Pl^^Aman^pa;>' years of age who has his business affairs\n,li l'\" l| li<- work. 1!\" will\nHHHHHHSHhA \"I it. hut lln- la -no, J.m. i-< i\n\u25a0irth more than dollars.\nW i: i!i al l v. i 1 ill a 111 giv. 11l\n\u2018ft '\u2022*A 1 r I 1 \u25a0thin.-\nare wanted. Win i ~.-ed.-d the uoi i;\nrated their ability.\n\nCONSCIENCE.\nWe advised to do and act as our conscience die-1\ntates. For instance should we have a desire to play cards and feel\nthat it is altogether rigjxt to do so, by all means gratify that de\nsire, and play cards. On the other hand should we derive keen\nenjoyment from dancing yet realize that our conscience does not\nsanction this form of amusement, would not our enjoyment be\nmore lasting if we should refrain? The same applies toother\nmore serious forms of amusement or entertainment. But are we\naltogether sure our conscience approves or disapproves as the case\nmay be? Do we not sometimes overlook the wee small voice and\nwith no intention whatever of doing wrong just \u201cfollow the 1\ncrowd?\u201d it is perfectly safe to drift with the current just so\nFlong as we remain in calm, peaceful waters, but look out for shoals,\ntoe ware of storms and swift currents. It is well to head or not al\ntogether ignore tfte voice of conscience. It may help the frail\ncraft .of-human life to steer clear of the deeper, more dangerous\ncurrents and carry us safely into port.\ni\nTHE MOVING CROWD.\nThe increasing number of people who rent a farm for the\ntertn of a year, and who soon move on somewhere else, is one of\nthe most unfortunate features of country life. Every time one\nmeets one of these outfits dragging dilapidated furniture over the\nroad, one is tempted to stop them, and ask if they ever- heard that,\na rolling stone gathers no moss?\nThree moves are said to be equal to a fire. The damage to fur- J\nniture is something, but that is only an incident. The real loss is I\nthat when a man settles in a new location, he has to change ovei\nhis methods to fit his locality. Moving involves a great deal of\nwork, and there is at least a month\u2019s time lost in every such\nchange.\nWORCESTER DEMOCRAT AND THE LEDGERENTERHUSE\nPUBLIC SALE\nOF A CARLOAD OF\nMISSOURI MULES.\nWe, the undersigned, will sell at the\nstables of Calvin Ei. Townsend, in Po\ncomoke City, Maryland, on\nSATURDAY, MARCH 19th, 1921\nbeginning at 2 o\u2019clock p. m.\na carload of choice Missouri Mules.\nWe have sold several carloads of\nMules here this season but we can\nassure you this is as fine a load as we\nhave ever offered. You know the\nkind of stock we have been selling,\ncome and look these fellows over,\nthey will suit you. They range in age\nfrom four to six years old and in\nweight from 1000 to 1300 pounds.\nThey are the kind that will suit the\ntrade in this section; all well broken\nand ready to go right to work. They\nwill arrive a few days before the saie\nand you are invited to inspect them.\nThe sale will take place rain or shine\nTERMS OF SALE\u2014Four months\ncredit will be given, the purchaser to\ngive bankable note with approved se\ncurity, or all cash at the option of the\npurchaser.\nG. C. CHINN\nMcCARTY BROS.\nEWELL CHILD, Attorneys-at-Law\nNOTICE TO CREDITORS\nNotice is hereby given that the sub\nscriber has obtained from the Orph\nans\u2019 Court for Worcester County,\nMaryland letters! of Administration\non the personal estate of\nMARY A. PARADEE\nlate of Worcester County, deceased.\nAll persons having claims against\nthe deceased, are hereby warned to\nexhibit the same, with the vouchers\nthereof, to the subscriber, on or be\nfore the 13th day of September, 1921.\nThey may otherwise by law be ex\ncluded from all benefits of the sain\nestate. All persons indebted to said\nestate are requested to make imme\npayment. Given under my hand this\n7th day of March, 1921.\nULYSSES G. PARADEE,\nAdministrator.\nTest:\u2014\nASBURY C. RILEY,\nRegister of Wills.\nBafcteies\nI i\nat a\n\nNew Price\ni\nLevel\nI\nEffective with the i\npublication of this an\nnouncement, Willard\nBatteries will be sold on\na new and materially\nlower price level.\nThe same Willard\nquality\u2014 backed, by the\nsame authorized Wil\nlard Service.\ni\nPocomoke Battery Co.\nCorner Front and Willow Streets\nTelephone 117\nPocomoke City, Maryland.\nVulcanizing\nWillard\nf Batteries\ni\ni\nKIRSC HbT U M\nFOR EASTER \u2014AND AFTER I\nThatrun-do wn-at-the-heel look will\ndo no longer. The old plea of high